05113nam a22006495i 9780822391173DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223911737 a10.1515/97808223911732doi  a(DE-B1597)553587  a(OCoLC)1224278956  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aLC3735.B5bG87 2009 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a370.117/509842221 aGustafson, Bret, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNew Languages of the State :bIndigenous Resurgence and the Politics of Knowledge in Bolivia /cBret Gustafson; K. Tsianina Lomawaima, Joanne Rappaport, Alcida Rita Ramos, Florencia E. Mallon. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b8 photographs, 1 table, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNarrating Native Histories00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbout the Series -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcronyms -- tOn Languages and Labels -- tIntroduction Ethnographic Articulations in an Age of Pachakuti -- tPart 1. Resurgent Knowledge -- tPart 2. Transnational Articulations -- tPart 3. Return to Struggle -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the mid-1990s, a bilingual intercultural education initiative was launched to promote the introduction of indigenous languages alongside Spanish in public elementary schools in Bolivia's indigenous regions. Bret Gustafson spent fourteen years studying and working in southeastern Bolivia with the Guarani, who were at the vanguard of the movement for bilingual education. Drawing on his collaborative work with indigenous organizations and bilingual-education activists as well as more traditional ethnographic research, Gustafson traces two decades of indigenous resurgence and education politics in Bolivia, from the 1980s through the election of Evo Morales in 2005. Bilingual education was a component of education reform linked to foreign-aid development mandates, and foreign aid workers figure in New Languages of the State, as do teachers and their unions, transnational intellectual networks, and assertive indigenous political and intellectual movements across the Andes.Gustafson shows that bilingual education is an issue that extends far beyond the classroom. Public schools are at the center of a broader battle over territory, power, and knowledge as indigenous movements across Latin America actively defend their languages and knowledge systems. In attempting to decolonize nation-states, the indigenous movements are challenging deep-rooted colonial racism and neoliberal reforms intended to mold public education to serve the market. Meanwhile, market reformers nominally embrace cultural pluralism while implementing political and economic policies that exacerbate inequality. Juxtaposing Guarani life, language, and activism with intimate portraits of reform politics among academics, bureaucrats, and others in and beyond La Paz, Gustafson illuminates the issues, strategic dilemmas, and imperfect alliances behind bilingual intercultural education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aEducationxSocial aspectszBolivia. 0aEducation, BilingualzBolivia. 0aEthnologyzBolivia. 0aGuarani IndiansxEducationzBolivia. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEducationzBolivia. 0aIndigenous peopleszBoliviaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aLomawaima, K. Tsianina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMallon, Florencia E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRamos, Alcida Rita, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRappaport, Joanne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.